WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.480
 Hello, and welcome to our lecture on JavaScript and the browser.

00:00:03.480 --> 00:00:05.280
 So JavaScript is a programming language,

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:08.480
 but more importantly, it typically runs in the browser.

00:00:08.480 --> 00:00:11.480
 In the browser, there are some special things.

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:13.480
 If you're just writing Python, right,

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:16.080
 you've got this whole operating system,

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:17.920
 whether it's Windows or Mac or Linux,

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:21.400
 that threads things, that allows you to write a piece of code

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:26.400
 that says, put out a prompt, wait for some input.

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:29.080
 When the input comes, write a loop,

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:33.920
 make a URL lib request, wait for that request.

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:37.080
 When that request comes, open up a database connection,

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:38.360
 put that data in the database.

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:40.280
 And there's this whole thing where you're like,

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:42.800
 go wait, go wait, go wait.

00:00:42.800 --> 00:00:44.720
 And operating system is taking care of the fact

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:49.200
 that your laptop keeps working while this program is waiting.

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:54.360
 But that's not how it works in JavaScript in the browser.

00:00:54.360 --> 00:00:55.480
 In the JavaScript in the browser,

00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:59.080
 this whole idea of waiting for something isn't anathema

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:02.280
 because it does what's called cooperative multitasking.

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:03.240
 And so in some ways,

00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:05.440
 JavaScript is not just a programming language,

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:08.640
 but it's also kind of part of what we think of typically

00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:10.520
 as the operating system.

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:12.880
 We got to help the browser work with things

00:01:12.880 --> 00:01:15.400
 like document object model being updated,

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:17.680
 the visible window being scrolled and tabs,

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:18.920
 multiple tabs are going on,

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:21.800
 events are happening and timers are happening.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:26.320
 And we have much more responsibility in the browser

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:31.080
 than we do sort of in Python just running on your laptop.

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:34.360
 So there's a couple of places that JavaScript can execute.

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:36.480
 Inline is the documents being parsed.

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:40.040
 At this point, document parsing stops

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:41.160
 and then JavaScript runs.

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:42.640
 You can take over.

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:46.800
 You can throw away all the rest of the document if you want.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:48.280
 Or there's some kind of a UI event,

00:01:48.280 --> 00:01:50.720
 like a click or something else happening,

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:54.080
 a resize of a window or a timer can expire

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:55.920
 or some asynchronous activity

00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:58.960
 like a retrieval of some data finishing

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:01.280
 and then activates your code.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:04.400
 Now, the key thing we talked about this in JavaScript

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:06.400
 is that first-class functions

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:08.560
 are essential to this execution model

00:02:08.560 --> 00:02:12.240
 because we have to basically say when this happens,

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:15.200
 run this code and the code is data.

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:18.080
 And so to some degree we say set something up

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:22.120
 and I'm handing you some code to handle this event.

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:27.040
 So let's take a look at this 01noscript.htm.

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:28.760
 This has no JavaScript.

00:02:28.760 --> 00:02:31.000
 And we've been talking about this all along

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:32.760
 where something comes from the server.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:36.040
 Here we have a header tag, H1 tag, and a P tag.

00:02:36.040 --> 00:02:38.600
 We parse, the browser parses that response

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:41.320
 and then writes the document object model.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:43.040
 And so when you do an inspect element,

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:45.920
 you're actually not seeing the exact text

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:48.400
 that came from the server.

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:51.320
 You are seeing the document object model

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:55.680
 that the browser created as it read that document.

00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:57.000
 And so this whole parse response.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.120
 And in this particular page, there is no JavaScript.

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:01.960
 And so the JavaScript sort of is sitting there

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:04.720
 in your browser, but it's not currently active.

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:08.520
 Here is a completely different page.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:10.200
 And this is the sum total.

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:12.680
 It's a script tag, document.write,

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:16.000
 document.write, and a slash script.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.920
 There is no HTML in this page.

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:22.880
 And that's because as the document is being parsed,

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:24.040
 it sees the script tag,

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:26.840
 and then it runs JavaScript, the code.

00:03:26.840 --> 00:03:29.840
 Document is a predefined object,

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:31.960
 which is the document object model.

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:34.880
 Document.write allows you in JavaScript

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:37.840
 to write HTML into the DOM.

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:40.760
 So we write two lines, the exact same two lines

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:42.360
 that were in the previous example.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:43.960
 And so when that's all said and done,

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:45.160
 we run the parse response.

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:47.200
 There's no HTML in this.

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:50.280
 I've exaggerated this to make the point, of course.

00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:52.560
 We parse the response, we run the JavaScript,

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:55.640
 and the JavaScript writes the document object model.

00:03:55.640 --> 00:03:57.800
 The DOM belongs to JavaScript.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:01.320
 You, when you're writing JavaScript, you own the browser.

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:03.080
 You are in charge.

00:04:03.080 --> 00:04:06.320
 So if you look at the inspector,

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:08.360
 the source code that came was the script,

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:10.240
 these four lines of script and document.write,

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:12.640
 document.write, and script/script.

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:15.040
 But the document object model, when it's all said and done,

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:17.880
 is the same as in the previous example.

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:21.320
 Now, we've been doing this for a while.

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:26.080
 We've been making certain tags, like the anchor tag,

00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:29.800
 have an onClick event, and then we call some JavaScript.

00:04:29.800 --> 00:04:33.080
 Now this is my func, open, print, close, print, semicolon,

00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:35.840
 is some JavaScript, except it's inside of a string,

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:38.000
 which means it's being executed.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.920
 It's actually being parsed and executed

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:44.440
 at the moment that the click happens.

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:46.960
 And then in the script tag,

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:48.520
 we create a function called my func,

00:04:48.520 --> 00:04:52.360
 and just put nice little console.log i was clicked in there.

00:04:52.360 --> 00:04:56.720
 So the way this works is the HTML comes,

00:04:56.720 --> 00:04:58.880
 JavaScript doesn't actually run during the parsing,

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:01.320
 except to create the function, there's no other thing.

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:03.960
 It doesn't actually, the log doesn't come out.

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:07.000
 But then later, when the DOM is shown, there is an event.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.320
 You can see that there's an event

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:09.800
 associated with that anchor tag.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:13.000
 And if you look at the document object model with inspect,

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:14.480
 you see, oh, this one has an event.

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:16.640
 Well, it's kind of obvious this one has an event,

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:19.640
 because the onClick is our way of indicating

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:20.800
 that there's an event.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:25.120
 Now, after the page shows up,

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:28.720
 then you click on the word click me,

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:31.320
 and then the JavaScript runs.

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:33.920
 So JavaScript is from a string,

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:36.120
 the string is in a sense compiled or parsed

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:37.400
 or whatever you wanna say.

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:39.120
 And then the code runs.

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:44.120
 And so the onClick event is handed a string of source code.

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:47.080
 And again, first class function.

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:48.960
 We've been doing this all along.

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:50.960
 And if you go back and think about some of the things

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:52.880
 we used to use, we've been using onClick

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:56.000
 for things like the cancelP,

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:57.560
 so that we can do things in there.

00:05:57.560 --> 00:06:00.880
 We still, it's just a way to indicate JavaScript.

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:01.800
 You can call a function,

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:03.720
 or you can just put the JavaScript right there.

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:05.760
 Sometimes you'll see several lines of JavaScript

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:07.120
 in an onClick method.

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:11.400
 Another way to run the code is as the result of a timer.

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:13.920
 So here we have a page, it's got an h1,

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:15.880
 it's got a p tag, and it's got some script.

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:18.080
 And that's all part of the parsing of the response.

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:20.520
 Now the script basically runs,

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:24.920
 and it says define a function called my func,

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:27.600
 that says console log I was called when it's called later,

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.880
 and then setTimeout my func 5000.

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:32.080
 What that basically says,

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:34.800
 setTimeout runs immediately and returns immediately.

00:06:34.800 --> 00:06:37.440
 It does not wait, it's not like input in Python.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:40.200
 It doesn't wait, it happens instantly.

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:42.840
 You are registering a handler

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:46.480
 that's triggered five seconds afterwards.

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:48.280
 Then we say console log timer started.

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:49.560
 So if you look at the output,

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:52.160
 you see that the first thing that happened

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:54.800
 was that the timer was started.

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:58.640
 Now if you ran this, and you can, o4timer.htm,

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:01.480
 you run it, and then you count five seconds,

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:02.860
 and then it says I was called.

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:05.840
 So this is code that you defined,

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:09.480
 and you said I want this code to run after a delay.

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:11.120
 And that's one form of an event,

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:14.840
 a timer expiration event that causes your code to run.

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:16.800
 Now if you take a look at this,

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:20.560
 first class functions are essential to this, right?

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:23.480
 And so I've changed this, o5function.htm

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:24.700
 changes this a little bit.

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:26.640
 Now notice there is no parenthesis.

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:28.480
 Now if you put a parenthesis after my func

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:30.000
 in the setTimeout call,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.560
 it would actually then call my func,

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:33.680
 and the log would happen,

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:35.160
 and then you'd get null back,

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:37.360
 and the setTimeout would actually fail.

00:07:37.360 --> 00:07:40.520
 My func is itself, with no parenthesis,

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:41.760
 is a function reference.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:45.880
 And we can see this by adding console log my func to it.

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:47.560
 So now if you watch the console,

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:51.120
 you can see the variable my func being printed out.

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:53.000
 And what does it show?

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:54.400
 It shows a function.

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:57.960
 Like that's what's in my func with no parenthesis.

00:07:57.960 --> 00:07:59.880
 My func with a parenthesis calls my func,

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:02.720
 but my func without a parenthesis is the,

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:06.720
 in this case, parsed source code of the my func function.

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:09.000
 So first class functions are essential

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:10.520
 to all this eventing.

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:12.120
 So up next, we'll talk a little bit

00:08:12.120 --> 00:08:13.940
 about the document object model.

00:08:13.940 --> 00:08:16.520
 (upbeat music)

